{"title_page": "Sally Greene", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sally Greene\n| honorific_suffix = <small>[[OBE]]</small>\n| occupation         = Producer, Restaurateur\n| spouse             = Robert Bourne\n| website            = http://sallygreeneobe.com/\n}}\n\n'''Sally Greene''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} is a British entrepreneur, theatre [[impresario]], restaurateur and philanthropist. She is known for her restorations of the [[The Old Vic|Old Vic]] and [[Criterion Theatre|Criterion]] theatres in London\u2019s West End, as well the famous jazz venue [[Ronnie Scott's Jazz Club|Ronnie Scott\u2019s]]. Greene also co-produced [[Billy Elliot the Musical|Billy Elliott the Musical]] with [[Stephen Daldry]], and has worked as executive producer for multiple theatre, film and television projects through her production company Greene Light Stage. \n\nIn 2006, Greene received an OBE for services to drama.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/58196/supplement/1|title=New Years Honours - United Kingdom|last=|first=|date=29 December 2006|work=The London Gazette|access-date=24 May 2019|page=10}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nGreene is the daughter of lawyer and amateur playwright Basil Greene.\u00a0 She initially trained as an actress, before moving backstage as a stage manager.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2005/apr/03/theatre1|title='I'm a risk-taker, there's no doubt about it'|last=Cooke|first=Rachel|date=2005-04-03|work=The Observer|access-date=2019-05-24|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> Greene also wrote a theatre column for Tatler in the 1980s.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nGreene attended the [[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nShe is a former Labour Pary donor.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/new-labours-fixer-welcome-to-sallys-irresistible-salon-139860.html</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nGreene\u2019s career in theatre began with the restoration of the [[Richmond Theatre]]. She bought the lease in 1987 before renegotiating it into a charitable trust with the local authority funding the restoration of the building.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lay-down-sally-222tjjn02s0|title=Lay down Sally|date=2006-07-09|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2019-05-24|language=en|issn=0956-1382}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992 Greene set up the Criterion Trust on a similar business plan, after which the theatre went under a complete restoration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2001/dec/03/careers.jobsadvice4|title=A hard act to follow|last=Kercher|first=John|date=2001-12-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-05-30|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1998, the Old Vic Theatre which is among Britain\u2019s oldest theatres, was in talks for development as an alternative venue, with speculation that it might become a nightclub or bingo hall, leading to an appeal by Culture Secretary [[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Chris Smith]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/125531.stm|title=BBC News {{!}} Entertainment {{!}} Old Vic theatre saved|website=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref>\n\nGreene formed The Old Vic Theatre Trust, which enlisted figures like [[Alexander Bernstein, Baron Bernstein of Craigweil|Alex Bernstein]] and Stephen Daldry. The Trust bought the building, offering an initial payment of \u00a31.5 million, which was later supplemented by a further \u00a32 million to transfer the ownership from the previous owner [[Ed Mirvish]] into the charitable trust.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 2003 she formed the Old Vic Theatre Company.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1994 Greene founded Greene Light Stage, which she runs alongside CEO and Producer Rebecca Quigley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2017/joseph-smith-joins-elton-johns-theatre-company-producer/|title=Joseph Smith joins Elton John\u2019s theatre company as producer|last=Masso|first=Giverny|date=2017-02-27|website=The Stage|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref> The company has been involved in over 100 shows including Billy Elliott the Musical with Stephen Daldry. The show first performed at the [[Victoria Palace Theatre]], in 2005.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2007 she launched Greene Light Films, which produces films and short films and made its first venture into television production in 2019.\n\nGreene owns prominent jazz venue [[Ronnie Scott|Ronnie Scott\u2019s]] Jazz Club in [[Soho]]. Together with philanthropist [[Michael Watt (philanthropist)|Michael Watt]], she took over from [[Pete King (saxophonist)|Pete King]] in 2005, and facilitated a complete refurbishment.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/leisure/10672134/How-Ronnie-Scotts-has-reversed-its-fortunes.html|title=How Ronnie Scott's has reversed its fortunes|last=Osborne|first=Alistair|date=2014-03-03|access-date=2019-05-24|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/4f986264-305f-11de-88e3-00144feabdc0|title=A London jazz club celebrates 50 years|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref>\n\nGreene also owns No. Fifty Cheyne, opened in 2004 as the [[Cheyne Walk]] Brasserie in Chelsea and relaunched in 2019 under the new name.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/luxury/drinking-and-dining/new-openings-sally-greenes-cheyne-walk-brasserie-reopens-no/|title=New Openings: Sally Greene's Cheyne Walk Brasserie reopens as No. Fifty Cheyne|last=Armstrong|first=Hilary|date=2019-04-08|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-05-24|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nGreene is a Trustee at the Old Vic Theatre Trust, the Criterion Theatre Trust, Greene Light Stage, Ronnie Scott\u2019s Charitable Foundation, and the London Music Fund.\n\n== Work ==\n\n=== Theatre ===\n\n* [[Billy Elliot the Musical|Billy Elliot: The Musical]] (producer)\n\n=== Film ===\n\n* 2007 [[Ruby Blue (film)|Ruby Blue]] (executive producer)\n* 2011 [[Hunky Dory (film)|Hunky Dory]] (executive producer)\n* 2014 [[Desert Dancer]] (executive producer)\n\n=== Television ===\nPlanned adaptation of the life of [[Joan Collins|Dame Joan]] and [[Jackie Collins]] (executive producer)\n\n== Personal life ==\nGreene is married to British property developer [[Robert Bourne (developer)|Robert Bourne]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/robert-bourne-and-sally-greene-l5bpjqqkgql|title=Robert Bourne and Sally Greene|date=2009-04-26|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2019-05-24|language=en|issn=0956-1382}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/sally-greene-475121 Sally Greene] at the [[Internet Broadway Database]] \n* [[imdbname:2295434|Sally Greene]] on [[IMDb]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British women in business]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) donors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sally Greene\n| honorific_suffix = <small>[[OBE]]</small>\n| occupation         = Producer, Restaurateur\n| spouse             = Robert Bourne\n| website            = http://sallygreeneobe.com/\n}}\n\n'''Sally Greene''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} is a British entrepreneur, theatre [[impresario]], restaurateur and philanthropist. She is known for her restorations of the [[The Old Vic|Old Vic]] and [[Criterion Theatre|Criterion]] theatres in London\u2019s West End, as well the famous jazz venue [[Ronnie Scott's Jazz Club|Ronnie Scott\u2019s]]. Greene also co-produced [[Billy Elliot the Musical|Billy Elliott the Musical]] with [[Stephen Daldry]], and has worked as executive producer for multiple theatre, film and television projects through her